         <abstract>
            <p>When one talks about market efficiency, it is important to distinguish between ideas whose implications are obvious and consequently travel quickly and ideas that require reflection and special expertise for their evaluation and consequently travel slowly. If the market is inefficient, it will not be inefficient with respect to the first kind of idea, which is unlikely to be misevaluated. Any market inefficiency, hence any investment opportunity, will arise instead with respect to the second kind. The second kind of idea -- rather than the obvious, hence quickly discounted, idea relating to "long-term" business or economic developments -- is the only meaningful basis for "long-term investing."</p>
          </abstract>
